04561nam a22008175i 9780813587417DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2017    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135874177 a10.36019/97808135874172doi  a(DE-B1597)526182  a(OCoLC)1013988631  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aBotkin, Frances R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aThieving Three-Fingered Jack :bTransatlantic Tales of a Jamaican Outlaw, 1780-2015 /cFrances R. Botkin, Frances R. Botkin. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b5  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Caribbean Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Representing Three-Fingered Jack -- t1. Divide and Conquer: Three-Fingered Jack and the Maroons -- t2. "Jack Is a MAN": Prose Obis, 1800-1870 -- t3. Staging Obi: Three-Fingered Jack in London and New York -- t4. Being Jack Mansong: Ira Aldridge and Three-Fingered Jack -- t5. After Emancipation: Masquerade and Miscegenation -- t6. Mansong : No Longer "Nearly Everybody Wite" -- tEpilogue: "The Baddest Man Around" -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe fugitive slave known as "Three-Fingered Jack" terrorized colonial Jamaica from 1780 until vanquished by Maroons, self-emancipated Afro-Jamaicans bound by treaty to police the island for runaways and rebels.  A thief and a killer, Jack was also a freedom fighter who sabotaged the colonial machine until his grisly death at its behest. Narratives about his exploits shed light on the problems of black rebellion and solutions administered by the colonial state, creating an occasion to consider counter-narratives about its methods of divide and conquer. For more than two centuries, writers, performers, and storytellers in England, Jamaica, and the United States have "thieved" Three Fingered Jack's riveting tale, defining black agency through and against representations of his resistance. Frances R. Botkin offers a literary and cultural history that explores the persistence of stories about this black rebel, his contributions to constructions of black masculinity in the Atlantic world, and his legacies in Jamaican and United States popular culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 4aCaribbean. 4afreedom fighter. 4ajack mansong. 4ajamaica. 4amansong. 4aoutlaw. 4arebel. 4athief. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBotkin, Frances R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Pilot eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311066330308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2017-2018z978311065742508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2018z978311066608340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813587417423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813587417.jpg  a978-3-11-065742-5  RUP eBook-Package 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066330-3  RUP Pilot eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-066608-3  RUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG